---
const realities = [
  {
    stat: 'Fifty vendors',
    body: 'A single regulated organisation routinely runs more than fifty disconnected SaaS tools — each with its own identity, its own audit log, its own contract.',
  },
  {
    stat: 'Every department buys its own tool',
    body: 'Procurement happens department by department. No-one owns the integration cost. No-one owns the access governance debt that piles up underneath.',
  },
  {
    stat: '2am incidents',
    body: 'When something goes wrong, the call goes to whichever vendor answers fastest. Accountability is split across half a dozen support contracts.',
  },
];
---

<section id="problem" class="section bg-surface">
  <div class="container-page">
    <header class="max-w-4xl">
      <p class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-sky-400">
        The problem
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
        Most organisations don't have a software problem.<br class="hidden sm:block" />
        They have a software sprawl problem.
      </h2>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-16 grid gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2 lg:gap-20">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-400">
          The reality today
        </h3>
        <ul class="mt-6 space-y-6">
          {realities.map((item) => (
            <li class="border-l-2 border-navy-900 pl-5">
              <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy-900">{item.stat}</p>
              <p class="mt-2 text-base leading-relaxed text-ink-600">{item.body}</p>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-400">
          The diagnosis
        </h3>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-ink-600">
          <p>
            This is not a technical problem. It is an organisational one. Software sprawl is the natural outcome of two decades of procurement-led tool adoption: every team picks the best point solution, no-one is accountable for the seams between them.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result is identity that lives in fifty places, audit trails that don't reconcile, and a compliance posture that is only as strong as the weakest vendor on the stack. For regulated organisations, that posture is no longer defensible.
          </p>
          <p class="border-l-2 border-sky-400 pl-5 text-lg font-medium text-navy-900">
            The answer is not more integrations. The answer is consolidation on a platform built for sovereignty from the ground up.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
